  <body style="background-color: black; background-image: url(&quot;spacebac.gif&quot;); color: yellow;">
    <h1 align="center"> NØNJY Amateur Radio </h1>
    <hr style="width: 1276px; height: 2px; color: yellow; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
    <em style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: 27.648px; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><font
        color="#ffff00"><strong></strong></font></em>
    <div style="text-align: center;"><em style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: 27.648px; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><font
          color="#ffff00"><strong>Home Page</strong></font></em></div>
    <div style="text-align: center;"><img src="file:///home/rick/n0njy_amateur_radio/images/n0njy_shack_colorado.jpg"
        alt="" title="Old Shack" style="width: 632px; height: 474px;"></div>
    <div style="text-align: center;">Rick's old shack back in Colorado.</div>
    <div style="text-align: center;"><br>
    </div>
    <div style="text-align: center;"><br>
    </div>
    <p style="text-align: left;">Welcome to my amateur radio pages. I do a lot
      of writing, but not always about Ham Radio.&nbsp; Most of that won't be
      here, there are links below for anything else you're looking for that I
      might write.&nbsp; On these pages, I will have information about Ham
      Radio, but this won't be a "blog-style" site.&nbsp; The pages will be more
      or less static.&nbsp; I tend to post things on Facebook these days on my
      Ham radio page, but if I write something important, I'll put i here as
      well.</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">As far as Amateur Radio goes, I'm not as active
      as I used to be, because I live on a sailboat these days and don't have as
      much room as I used to for the shack.&nbsp; The "Shack" these days
      consists of a very tiny area next to my Navigation station with an HF rig
      installed there.&nbsp; </p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">Current projects include some QRP radios, an
      S-Pixie transceiver that will be set up for 7.023 Mhz CW and a qrplabs.com
      QRX transceiver, that will cover the 20m band.&nbsp; My other project in
      the works is a 20/40 meter magnetic loop antenna that I can use while I'm
      visiting Colorado for the next few months.</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">My wife, JoAnne (KB0IRW) has had a recurrence
      of ovarian cancer and we've returned to our long-time home in Colorado,
      for her to receive treatment from her doctors, and see our children, and
      grandchildren (all of whom live here in Colorado).&nbsp; We will be here
      until such time as her chemotherapy is completed, probably in the early
      Spring-time, at which time we will depart and head back to our home aboard
      the Sailing Ketch "Adventure".&nbsp; Listed below is a link to our blog
      site "Winds of Time" for Adventure.</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">We've lived aboard now for over three years and
      will probably continue to live aboard the boat.&nbsp; Our plans are to
      make a trip to the Bahamas in the spring, once we get back aboard.</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">Over the years I've operated everything from
      TNOS (a TCP/IP packet system) to RTTY, packet on multiple frequencies, CW,
      bpsk (which I currently operate from the ship), SSB, AM, FM and many other
      modes on multiple bands.&nbsp; I ran a full packet station on multiple
      frequencies in the 1990s and early 2000s in Colorado Springs.&nbsp; Before
      I was a Ham, I ran dial up bulletin board systems using Apple computers
      (Apple ][+, Apple //e etc, not Macs).</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">Before I was a ham, I was an avid shortwave
      listener, and actually started building crystal radios at the ripe old age
      of eight years old.&nbsp; Because Morse Code (and other languages) always
      got the best of me, I never became a Ham until I was much older.&nbsp;
      When I was 10 years old, I received a junked Shortwave receiver from a
      neighbor who saw me playing with crystal sets.&nbsp; I repaired it (dirty
      potentiometer, replaced a couple of dried electrolytic capacitors and a
      couple of tubes) and had it up and running in a day or two.&nbsp; I strung
      my very first dipole antenna up the day I got it working, with my Dad's
      assistance, and never looked back.</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">Electronics became my life.&nbsp; I ran a TV
      shop at the age of 16, out of my basement, as well as had a lawn care
      business that I ran on the side.&nbsp; I joined the US Air Force in 1976
      (signed up late in 1975) and went on to retire from the USAF in
      2002.&nbsp; I worked for the Missile Defense Agency for 18 years as well,
      from 1997 - 2015 (I was in the USAF Reserves by 1989) and retired finally
      in 2015 to sail away on Adventure.&nbsp; (Scroll down for a picture of my
      wife, JoAnne (KB0IRW) and myself standing on the deck of s/v Adventure).</p>
    <p style="text-align: left;">Below are a few links to take you to various
      pages.&nbsp; Some are mine, some are not.&nbsp; I'll add others as I
      create them and find them necessary.&nbsp; There is information about me
      on <a href="http://qrz.com" title="http://qrz.com" target="_blank">QRZ.com</a>,
      and you can reach me at <a href="mailto:n0njy@qsl.net" title="Email" target="_blank">n0njy@qsl.net</a>.&nbsp;
      I respond to most email unless it's spam.&nbsp; </p>
    <p style="text-align: center;"><br>
    </p>
